@flexiarg relationship-coherence/meeting-the-people
@title Fold Each Other's People (and Pets) Into the Shared Circle
@sigils [🫂/圈]
@keywords introductions, friends, family, pets, approval, inclusion, social-expansion, third-parties
@audience correspondents widening a two-person world
@references [relationship-coherence/parallel-lives-mirroring relationship-coherence/rupture-repair]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-05-03 — Joe, 'thanks for coming over & meeting my dad, it was fun!'; the move recurs as approvals and inclusions are tracked (2026-04-14 'you have approval from my dad'; 2026-05-06 Chris: 'Looks like you've got yourself a boyfriend!'; dogs Zero and Freddie folded in as proxies)."]
@tone declarative
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a friend, family member, or pet enters one person's orbit, narrate the introduction and track their approval and inclusion — the couple's world widens by absorbing each other's people.

  + context: A bond between two people is also a bond between two social worlds (Chris, Frankie, the family, the book group; Zero and Freddie). Much of the correspondence reports these meetings and reactions.

  + IF:
    someone from one person's life (person or animal) comes into contact with the pair, or could.

  + HOWEVER:
    third parties also import judgement (a friend's 'not a good pairing'); folding people in means metabolising their verdicts, not only their welcome — and inclusion must be mutual, not one-sided.

  + THEN:
    introduce and report back warmly, note who approves and who is now 'in', and process any hostile verdict together rather than letting it land privately (see relationship-coherence/rupture-repair).

  + BECAUSE:
    a relationship gains durability by being witnessed and held by a widening circle; tracking approval/inclusion is how the couple knits itself into the surrounding social fabric.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: each other's people are met, named, and increasingly shared. Failing when: the bond stays hidden from both social worlds, or an outsider's verdict is absorbed alone instead of together.
